 healing power\nhighly concentrated, active and persistent.\nItching stops and the skin feels\nImmeasurably grateful. In the treatment\nof virulent eczema, acne, pimples i\nand all mirface affections, Poalam's results\nare quickly felt and,?een.\nSold everywhere. Fore free sample i\nwrit* to Emergency Laboratories, 243\nWest 47th St., New York City.\nPoslam Soap, medicated with Foslam,\nshould be used if skin is tender and\nensltlve.\nOLD STANDBY, FOR\nACHES AND PAINS\nAny man or woman who keeps\nSloan's handy will tell you\nthat same thing\nESPECIALLY those frequently\nattacked by rheumatic twinges.\nA counter-irritant, Sloan's Liniment\nscatters the congestion and penrtrate$\nwithout rubbing to the afflicted\npart, soon relieving the ache and pain.\nKept handy and used everywhere\nfor reducing and finally eliminating the\npains and aches of lumbago, neuralgia,\nmuscle strain, joint stiffness, sprains,\nKmn'aoa ami fli?. ?r\\m111 r\\f nvnowtes\nYou just know from its stimulating,\nhealthy odor that it will do you good!\nSloan's Liniment is sold by all druggists?36c.\n70e, $1.40.\nSloarts\nIiniment(5s$\nCuticura Soapl\nAND OINTMENT\nClear the Skin\nSTOKES' OWN PEN I\nREFUTES CHAGRIN\nIN QUITTING YALE\nAction Not Inspired by the\nFact He Is Not to Sueceed\nHadley.\nFLAA A tA) L A K A(iU I\nMoved by Precedent and Desire\nto Give New President\nFree Rein.\nANGELL LIKELY CHOICE\nProcess of Elimination Makes\nHim Victor at Election\non Saturday.\nSpecial Despatch to Tub New Yobk Hekald.\nNew Haven, Feb. 16.?The roaigna- j\ntlon of the Rev. Dr. Anson Phelps,\nStokes as secretary of Yale University\non the eve of the selection of a successor\nto President Arthur Twining\nHadley provoked a variety of disquieting\nrumors. To Dr. Stokes the most\ndisagreeable inference drawn from his\nretirement after twenty yeare of notable\nservice was that he is leaving!\nbecause of chagrin?chagrin due to'\nthe knuwledg^ that the corporation of\nYale, at its meeting next Saturday, j\nwill not place him at the head of Yale.j\nThis particular rumor, which ran\nabout New Haven and quickly per-!\neolated to centres of Yale alumni elsewhere,\nis emphatically destroyed by\nthe letter of resignation which Dr.\nStokes sent to the President and Fellows\nof the University and which was\nmade public this afternoon. In downright\nfashion Dr. Stokes Informs the\nuniversity heads, and consequently the\nwhole world of Y'ale, that he thinks it\nbest to go out with President Hadley\nfor the reason that the new president\nof Yale would be free to select a i\nsecretary for himself, and for the fur- j\nther reason that he desires to take up\nother work.\nParticular Inquiry reveals that Dr.\nStokes's letter is entirolj disingenuous. I\nHis friends and numerous other persons\nintimately acquainted with the inner af- j\nfairs of the university are aware that 1\nhe made up his mind almost a year ego I\nto sever his connection with Yale. When\nhe was in China last Juno he wrote a\nletter to President Hadley in which he\nnotified the president of his intention\nto resign at the close of the Hadley\nadministration, and this letter was read\nto the corporation by President Hadley\nat an executive session neia lasi oeptember.\nThere is absolutely no reason to believe\nDr. Stokes is leaving Yale in a\ndisappointed or disgruntled frame of\nmind. Had Dr. Iladley elected to remain\nlonger in the presidency of the\nuniversity it is conceivable that Dr.\nStokes would have remained with him,\nfor the friendship between tho ^wo men\nis extremely close, and Dr. Stokes's\nloyalty to President Hadloy has been a\nbyword of admiration among Yale men.\nHut with Dr. Hadley out after twenty j\nyears, and out also at his own will and i\ndesire. Dr. Stokes feels that he, too.\nshould leave, making place for a new j\nuniversity secretary who will be sure to j\nhe In tunc and sympathy with tho new j.\nadministration that Yalo Is to have. In\nprivate conversation Dr. StokoH makts\nthese facts entirely clear. Ills friends\nknow he considers his period of usefulness\nat an end: that his affection for\nthe uhlverslty Impels him to believe\nthat a change may he beneficial all\naround.\nOne of the disquieting stories grow-\ning out of the situation was that President\nHadley Is being \"forced\" out. I\nCareful inquiry finds nothing to Justify I\nany such surmise. In the first place\nPresident Hadley is finishing twenty j\nyears of service as the director of 1\nYale's policies. Two decades const!- i\ntute the usual period of service for a j\npresident of Yale. Custom and expert-\nence have shown that a change in\npresidents after twenty years Is conducive\nto good results in university\nprogress. The second, more personal\nand moro definite reason is that Dr.\nHadley leaves Yale to take up his first\nlove In study, railroad economics. Bofore\nhe came here he was an authority\non the subject. HI* prestige as an expert\nIn railroad management and buM-,\nness haa grown In twenty years. He\nIs a member of the exocutive board of\nthe Atchison. Topeka and Santa Fe\nRailroad. It Is his ardent desire to\nrenew his study of railroad economics\nand possibly to attach himself In a 1\ncloser business way to a railroad sys- 1\ntern that opens the Yale door outward\nfor him.\nThe new president will be named next\nI ME1\n1 TRJUS\nI OF TH1\nI 60 WALL ST\nI For 1\npUNDS\ncurities\nspecific in\\\nSuch fund\nWe invite\nform of de\n\nTHE NET\nWOMEN SUN W\nBURY RELATI\nSecretly Lay Body in Ger\ncago Studio as Thej\ncantations\nSpecial Despatch to Tub New Yobk Hbbald.\nChicaoo. Feb. 1?.?a grewsome mystery.\nmade more Impenetrable through\nIts seeming connection with a number\nof mediaeval cults, came to a melodramatic\nend at dawn to-day when a spade\nIn the hands of a Dolice searcher un\ncovered the secret grave of Mrs. Nancy\nM. Chamberlln, SI years old, missing\nsince last June.\nWithout shroud or coffin, the aged\nwoman's body had been laid to lta final\nrest In a geranium bed at the rear ol\nthe studio In which she had lived wltr\nher daughter and granddaughter a!\nFifty-seventh street and Stony Island\navenue. Two women had dug her grave\nand had murmured over her at midnight\nthe age old responses of the\nChaldean sun worshippers.\nJust before the recovery of the body\na full description of these mysterious\nrites was given to the police by Miss\nMarian Townsend, the granddaughter\nwho yesterday had maintained through\nseveral hours of questioning that she\ndid not know where her grandmothei\ncould be found. Until this morning Miss\nTownsend's answers to the examiners\nmerely had been the echo of those of her\nmother, Mrs. Ruth Townsend\n\"She is happy and well cared for In\n'ove.\"\nSaturday, it Is taken for granted. On\nthat day the corporation of Yale, the\nsixteen all powerful directors of the university's\ndestinies, meets to unravel the\nknot that has bothered Yale for many\nmonths, the presidential tangle. There\nis excellent reason to believe the choice\nof the corporation for President Hadley's\nsuccessor will be James Rowland\nAngell, head of the Carnegie Corporation.\nPersons here are completely satisfied,\nafter talking with members of the\ncorporation, thRt Prof. Angell has virtually\nbeen decided on and that he has\nalready been Informally notified.\nOne of the questions that agitated the\ncorporation and, In truth, the alumr.l\nwas whether a Yale man should be\ncalled to the headship of Yale. The\nfeeling is believed to be strongly against\nthat Course. The dominant theory' war\nthat It would be better to try the experiment\nof calling to the presidency ;i\nnon-Yale man, some one obviously\nqualified In scholarship and executive\nublllty who would not have strictly n\n\"Yale\" point of view. Prof. Angell\nqualified accurately in this respect, as\nhe was graduated from the University\nof Michigan, where his father. Dr. James\nBurr 111 Angell, diplomat and student ol\ninternational law, was president for\nthirty-eight years, studied at Harvard\nand then became a member of the facul\nlien ot me university or Minnesota aim\nthe University of Chicago?acting president\nat the latter for a year.\nThe retirement of tne Rev. Dr. Anson\nPhelps Stokes is an event of actual sadness\nto thousands of Yale men who came\nto have a deep regard for Dr. Stokes in\nthe twenty years of his service. It is\nrecognized that he contributed mightily\nto the power and dignity of the university.\nlie Is the son and namesake of\nAnson Phelps Stokes. New York banker\nand philanthropist, who died some years\nago. He was a graduate of the class of\n1896 and was selected by President Hadley\nto bo secretary of Yale when Hadley\nentered upon his own incumbency in\n1899.\nDr. Stokes's letter, withheld until this\nafternoon, and which he states Is perfectly\n\"explicit,\" is in part as follows:\n\"To the President and Fellows of Yale\nUniversity:\n\"Gentlemen?I beg to submit formally\nmy resignation as secretary of Yale University,\nto tako effect at the close of the\npresent university year. The members\nof the corporation will remember that at\nthe executive session in September the\npresident read my letter to him from\nGhina under date of June 18, 1920, in\nwhich, after explaining the reasons for\nmy decision. I expressed the opinion that\n'the corporation should know, what I am\nsure you at least have personally long\nrealized, that, although X shall count it a\nprivilege to retain my office during tne\ncoming year, It Is my Intention to resign\nthe secretaryship next June.' I suggestpd\nthat my letter be read to the corporation,\nbut requested the president to \"defer\nany public announcement until It Is followed\nat the proper time by a formal letter\nof resignation addressed to the president\nand fellows.'\n\"As the letter is written before the\ncorporation has announced its decision,\nmy action cannot be misinterpreted as\ndue to any lack of sympathy with the\ncorporation's choice. It also seems to\nme only fair to the university that my\nresignation should be formally presented\nat tills time so that the new president\nwill be in a poifltoln to act promptly in\nseeking a new secretary.\n\"The deelWon to resign the secretaryship\nwhen Mr. Hadley resigned the presidency\nis one of many years' standing. It\nIs In accord with the precedent established\nbv mv predecessor. It seems bet\ntor, from the standpoint of the university,\nthat a president should have In\nthis oflloe some ono chosen by him.\n\"With assurance of my appreciation of\nthe unfnlllnic courtesy and consideration\nshown me by the president and fellows\nthe past twenty years, I am, with\npreat reaped, very truly yours,\n\"Ansox Phelps Stokes.\n\"February 7. iWl.\"\niftflEjIi 'I\nritopoLr\nT COMR\nI CITY OF NEW\nREET 716 FIF\n_,ATER INVEST]\nwhich you collect from mai\ni and which you arc holding\nvestment should not be left id\ns will earn interest if deposite\nyou to consult our officers,\nposit best suited to your requir\nW YORK HERALD. TH\nORSHIPPERS\nVE, 91, IN YARD\nanium Bed in Rear of Chir\nChant Mediaeval Inat\nMidnight.\nBut after a sleepless night, separated\nfrom the woman who appeared to domi\nInato all her actions, she cried out hys\nterlcally that she \"wished to tell about\ngrandmother and end all tills frightful\nmystery.\"\n1 This is the fltr.rv tha tri ?-l irvl/l t a th?\npolice:\n\"Grandmother closed her eyes. I do\nnot remember when It was. It was some j\ntime last June. She died a natural death\nas the world looks upon death. We do\nnot believe that she la dead. Mother and j\nI buried her in the geranium bed behind\nour studio.\"\nThen she launched at once Into a\nweird narrative of the preparations for\nthe midnight burial and the fantastic j\nj rites that accompanied It. The flower I\n1 bed had been planted In geraniums, at j\nthat time in full flower.\nMrs. Townsend went out Into the yard\nat sunset and dug them up, replanting\nthem In a neighbor's garden. Then she 1\nreturned to the house, and she and her i\ni daughter llghte.d a candle in honor of\nthe sun god, and prostrated themselves\nIn supplication to the \"All Wise and all\ni Good.\"\ni They were silent as the mantle clock\nchimed midnight. Then, still singing\nthe sun god's chants, they carried the\ni body out into the yard and laid It In\nthe grave.\nPROBLEM OF ALIENS\nDIVIDES AUDIENCE\n1,000 at Economic Club Dinner\nHear Arguments For and\nAgainst Restriction.\nIn a discussion of the immigration\nproblem at a dinner of the Economic\nClub attended by nearly 1,000 persons\nat .the Hotel Astor last night the speakers\nwho favored restriction and those\nwho did not found equal support among\nthe audience. The discussion warmed\ninto debate, with I'rof. Jeremiah W.\nj Jenks of New York University and Elon\nHuntington Hooker speaking for further\nrestriction, and President La Guard la. of\nthe Board of Aldermen and Louis Mar;\nJ shall pleading for a continuance of the\nI established policy.\n.Mr. Marshall said the same clamor for\n'restriction arose in 1R20 when the Irish)\nJ began to come, and again when the Ger- j\nI mans and tljen the Scandinavians fir:-t\nj emigrated in numbers. He could see no\nreason why the laws as they stand, prohibiting\nthe admission of all persons\nmentally, morally or physically unfit,\narc not sufficient, provided they are\nproperly enforced. Ho asked for better\ninspection of arrivals and the correction\ni of tho exploitation of Immigrants.\nProf. Jenks Insisted that tho ten|\ndency of recent Immigration was toward\nthe lowering of American standards of\nliving, and declared that our policy must j\nbe changed if we arc to assimilate properly\nand Americanize those who come i\nhere. He favored the Dillingham bill.\n\"The time has come,\" Mr. Hooker\nsaid, \"to shift the burden of proof. The\nImmigrant must show cause why he\nshould come In rnther than that the\nUnited States should prove him to be un- j\nworthy. Those now coming in arc largely\na rnce untrained by Inheritance to\nappreciate the Institutions, laws ar.d\ncustoms of this country- They multiply\nour problems unduly even In comparison\nwith their number. From their ranks\ncome a large proportion of the radicate,\nterrorists and a number of tho criminal\nclasses. The A. F. of I?. estimates that\n2,One.0.00 men are out of work. Tdle|\nness needs constructive, not destructive,\nleadership.\"\nj President La Ouardia took exception j\nto Mr. Hooker's statement that 25 per\nj cent, of the drafted men examined In\nj army camps couid not read or write a i\nj letter home. \"That Is accurately stated.'* j\n1 he said, \"but Mr. Hooker forgets to\nj mention that these men also fought and I\ni died a a Americans. And as for the per-\nI centage of the physically unfit, what is j\nI that but a reflection upon* our industrial\nI conditions?\n\"Immigration laws will not stop the\nspread of Bolshevism. The only way to\nstop that is by obtaining tho confidence j\nof the people in this country through i\nhonest and efficient Government.\" Mr.\nT<a Guardia also stressed the need for:\ni improved conditions at Ellis Island.\nWINS I35.000 CLAIM O.V B. R. T.\nA jury before Supreme Court Justice\nManning In Brooklyn returned a verdict\ni yesterday of $35,000 In favor of Law-\nrenec J. Laughlln, a salesman of 206\nI Sterling place, and against the B. R. T.\nOn October II, 1S19, Laughlln's left\nlog was crushed In a collision between\na Fifth and a Sixteenth avenue car at\nFiatbush ai\\d Fourth avenues, Brooklyn.\nLaughlin was a passenger on the Six- I\nteenili avenue car. He said he lost\n$5,000 In wages and paid doctor's bills\naggregating almost $3,000. He sued for\n$100,000.\nrAN J\nANY\nr YORK, I\nTH AVENUE I\nV1ENT I\nCuring se- I\nI for some I\nle.\nd here.\nas to the\nements.\nI\nr 0*0\n.1\nURSDAY, FEBRUARY\nFORD IS WARNED\nON JEW BAITING\nPresident of Detroit 'Times'\nHints That Demand for\nCars May Fall Off.\nASKS SHOW OF PROOF\nJames Schermerhorn Says\nChallenge of Malijrned People\nIs Undodgable.\nSpecial Despatch to Thb New Yo?k Herald.\nDetroit, Feb. 16. James Schermerhorn,\npresident of the Detroit Timea,\ncommenting to-day on the offer by Jewish\norganizations to finance an Investigation\non allegations made airalnst them\nby Henry Ford, through his paper, the I\nDearborn Independent, said\n\"It is asking a good deal of the Indefatigable\nHenry Ford to make out a\ncaso of Semitic conspiracy against the\nworld and to prove It, too. Besides,\nwhen the Jew baiting is booming the\ncirculation of the Dearborn Independent, i\nmaking ten copies circulate where one\ncirculated before, what other evidence j\ncan the Je>vs of Detroit ask for that Mr. j\nFord is engaged In a Just and world sav- j\nlng enterprise?\n\"Besides, establishing the authenticity\nof the alleged protocols and confirming\nail the fulminatlons against the Jewish\nrace might Impose too heavy a burden\nupon that branch of the Ford Industries.\n\"The Jewish organizations that chal- j\nlenge Henry Ford's sensational revelations\nand his sincerity must realize that i\nhis literary output, like all other forms j\nof production In his great plant, must be 1\nentrusted to other hands, and It may be\nexpecting too much of an overworked department\nto produce all these fierce becudgollngs\nof the Jews every week and\naccept an order to prove that there Is\nanything In the product but prejudice,\npersecution and poppycock.\n\"But the challenge of a maligned people\nIs direct, undodgeable stuff for all\nthat. Henry Ford Is not so useful and\nsuccessful In his day and generation that j\nhe can afford to Ignore it.\n\"He should enmo out into the open and\nJustify his bitter and sweeping ussailing\nof the rectitude of his Jewish fellow citizens\nor close down forever this department\nof his activities when he resumes\nmaximum production lr. all the rest of\nhid* works. or the tlmo is liable to come\nwhen he will need something less than\nmaximum production to satisfy the demand\nfor his products. Stranger things\nhave happened In the history of mixing\nwholesale insulting with wholesale manufacturing.\"\nSAYS STEEL PRICES\nCHECK READJUSTMENT\nRepresentative Black Regrets\nGary's Announcement.\nSpecial Despatch to The New York Herald.\nNew York Herald nnrran, I\nWashington. D. C.. Feb. IS. j\nThe United States Steel Corporation\nby refusing to reduce its prices Is\nhampering tho economic readjustment\nnow in progress and the return of prosperity,\nKepresentatlvo Black fTexas)\ncharged in a fpecch to tho Houso today.\nMr. Black attacked organizations of\nboth capital and labor which are attempting\nto maintain the wartime ecAle\n?u uiviurnuji unu wii^n, A^utuivuiQ is\nnow hearing tho brunt of tho readjustment.\nfarm products showing the greatest\ndecrease tn price, he said.\n\"*vith st>el such a basic material. It\nla regrettable that Judge Filbert H. Gary,\nci.airman of the 1'nlted .States Steel\nCorporation, has announced that prices\nof steel will not be reduced. It means\nfurther delay In the process of readjustment.\nBusiness will not be normal\nuntil a bushel of wheat or a pound of\npork or a halo of cotton will buy as\nmuch steel as It did In 1914.\n\"Tie United .States Sleel Corporation\nmade a profit of jmt.OOO.'iOO in 1930. as\nagainst 171,000,000 In 1314. Surely it can\nafford to reduce prices of steel without\nlarge reductions In wages. Unless the\nlarge corporations set their houses In\norder. Congress may have to aet.\nHighly organized capital and highly\norganized labor must be willing to acHlghly\norganized capital and highly organized\nlabor must be willing to accept\nreductions or they will find themselvos\nengulfed in the economic adjustment\nnow sweeping the country. Steel prices\nare so vital to the country.- The continued\nhigh level Is hampering building,\nthe normal resumption of which would\naid the country as mutfa as any other\nevent.\"\nNKWSP\\Pi:n DTVAMITF.O,\nRock Isi-anp. 111.. Feb. II.?The plant\nof the Rock Island .Vrtcs. a sensational\nweekly, was dynamited early to-day.\nThe plant was wrecked, but no one wa*<\nInjured. The .Vetra' home was destroyed\nby dyramite several years ago. The\neditor Is serving a year sentence for I\ncriminal llhcl.\nI A mrtr\nr KAINfk 15\nOffer ai\nLower Fifth\nAn Attractive\nWomen's Htgh\nPumps an\nStyles formerl\na much higher\nvalues of except\nLower Fifth\nBetween 26th\n1\n/1\n17, 1921.\nFEAR BIG TONG WAR;\nEIGHT CHINESE SHOT\nPolice on Pacific Coast Renew\nPrecautions With Three\nVictims Dead.\nHOP SING VS. BING KONG\nOutbreaks Are Expected in All\nPlaces Where Bivals Are\nLiving'.\nSpecial Despatch to Tub Kaw York\nLos Anoeles, Feb. 16.?Hop Sins\ngunmen on the Pacific coast are girding\nj themselves for battle with the Bins\nKong Tong. The shooting of eight of\ntheir members, three of whom were\nkilled Tuesday night, when a Chinese\nfestival was at its height, has fanned\nto flame 2,000 years of Hop Sing hatred\nfor the Blng Kong.\nIn all the coast cities where Chinese\ncolonies exist the police are taking\nevery precaution to prevent further\nTong reprisals. The local Chinatown,\nthough during the previous night\nabustle with activities of celestial\nmerrj makers, resembled a silent sepulchre\nt .ght The murder of two\nChinese mints and the wounding of\na third, ,>ig Kong, gunman, has in\n1 l?,? ,y,? r\\f\nJWlt'U U (I1U1UUI1U imi lUlw LUC ?>v w*\nChinatown's inhabitants. Ail shops were\nclosed and doors and windows were barricaded\nagainst invasion from an enemy\ntong. An unusually large number of\nuniformed patrolmen appeared in the\nstreets.\nIn San Francisco, where one Hop Sing\nman was killed and three others were\nwounded\" by rival highbinders, the deserted\nstreets of Chinatown were\nstrangely silent, while augmented police\nI squads kept a careful watch on the barricaded\ndens.\nI The police of Stockton are lnvestigat[\nlng the slaying of a llop Sing man in\nI that city who was attacked by Bing\nKong gunmen at the same hour Tuesday\nnight when the war was reopened\nIn I,os Angeles and San Francisco. Fear\nthat the tong strife will likewise occur\nin Fresno Is expected.\nPortland's Chinatown also showed\nsigns of extreme anxiety over the tong\nmurders In Loa Angeles.\nIn this city the two enemies faced\neach other In the city Jail, when eight\nHop Sing leaders endeavored to identify\nthe Bing Kong men who had done the\nactual shooting here. The fourteen ng\nKong suspects were bucked against a\nwall and the indignant Hop Sings car fully\nstudied their features. Fivo of the\nfourteen prisoners were pointed out as\nsome of the gunmen who fired the shots\nj that felled the three men.\n.luck \\V. Jung Gee Wing and Gam\nI Hang were accused by the Hop Sing\ni men of being thw ones who slew Soo Ho\n^Long. Jung and Lang, the Hop Sings\nsaid, entered the room and did the shooting,\nwhile Gee Wing remained at the\ndoor as \"lookie.\" Luck Suey was identified\nby the Hop Sing members as the\ngunman who harl shot Lew Hing tn the\nlegs. The others were also held on\ncharges of suspicion of murder.\nThose familiar with the customs of\nthe Chinese predict that the Hop Sings,\nknown as the most daring and dangerous\nof all tongs, will declare a coast\nj wide warfare on the Bing Kongs. Outbreaks\nare expected in all the cities\nwhero the Hop Sings and the Bing\nKongs rub elbows.\nHATFIELDHAD WALLET\nOF SLAIN DETECTIVE\nj Possession After Fight Not\nExplained in Court.\nWilliambom, W. Va.. Feb. 16.?9id\nHatfield, Chief of the Matewan police\nand otto of the nineteen defendant** on\ntrial here for alleged participation In the\nttfitflr. last Mnv. had tn his\npossession shortly after the fight the\npocketbook of Albert C. Kelts, the slain\nleader of the Baldwin-Kelts detectives at\nMatewan, according to Allen Johnson,\nthe first witness called to-day.\nJohnson, who Is a railroad man. was\nasked, \"What did Hatfield say?''\n\"He said, 'Much obliged, Mr. Fcls,'\nthe witness replied.\nOn cross-examination Johnson said hr.\n